,\n23\t  \"fix_hint\": \"Replace slide 7's figure with figures/NB01_fur_signature_scatter.png; rewrite title to 'Fur\\u2013Leaden concordance: \\u03c1=0.315, 71% sign agreement across 93 DEGs \\u2014 and a buffered respiratory cluster at y\\u22480'; rewrite caption to describe the concordant_strong vs buffered partition the figure visualizes. The NB00 sphingolipid orientation point can be reduced to one bullet on slide 6 (methods) since slide 16 already carries it.\"\n24\t}\n25\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7dbc6ac5-2e22-4737-9cd1-cf751888377b","uuid":"d32c2627-eb61-4570-a22d-7d59b23003f5","timestamp":"2026-06-07T16:32:55.876Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/aparkin/BERIL-research-observatory/projects/caulobacter_fur_lipida_loss/talks/draft_1/audit/revisions/F003.finding.json","content":"{\n  \"id\": \"F003\",\n  \"class\": \"claim_evidence\",\n  \"severity\": \"P1\",\n  \"confidence\": \"high\",\n  \"slide_id\": 7,\n  \"slide_position\": 7,\n  \"slide_layout\": \"data_figure\",\n  \"substory_id\": \"S1\",\n  \"title_quote\": \"NB00: sphingolipid biosynthesis is constitutive across the rescue strain series\",\n  \"issue\": \"Slide 7 is the S1 data_figure slot. S1's substory plan (02_substories.md, S1 'Slide kinds anticipated') explicitly calls for 'data_figure (R-slide \\u2014 Fur\\u2013Leaden concordance scatter, A1)' \\u2014 i.e. figures/NB01_fur_signature_scatter.png, which directly visualizes the Spearman \\u03c1=0.315 concordance that anchors Layer 1. Instead this slide shows the NB00 sphingolipid locus heatmap, whose substantive content is an S3 finding (constitutive sphingolipid pool). S1's defining quantitative finding (the Fur\\u2013Leaden concordance) has NO figure backing it anywhere in the deck \\u2014 slide 9 (the S1 claim slide) is bullets-only. Meanwhile the same NB00 figure is shown AGAIN on slide 16 (see F005), so the deck recycles an S3-belonging figure across two substories and never shows the figure that S1 actually needs.\",\n  \"report_evidence\": [\n    {\n      \"section\": \"\\u00a7NB01 image caption\",\n      \"quote\": \"Leaden \\u0394fur logFC vs our 4584-vs-4580 logFC; concordant_strong in dark blue, buffered set in orange, discordant in red\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"section\": \"\\u00a7NB01 \\u2014 Leaden 2018 Fur signature\",\n      \"quote\": \"The scatter shows the dramatic asymmetry between our amplified Fur-derepression cohort (top-right quadrant, exceeding Leaden's logFC) and the buffered cohort (cluster near y=0 spanning Leaden's full -9 to -5 range)\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"fix_target\": \"slide_compose.v1.md\",\n  \"fix_hint\": \"Replace slide 7's figure with figures/NB01_fur_signature_scatter.png; rewrite title to 'Fur\\u2013Leaden concordance: \\u03c1=0.315, 71% sign agreement across 93 DEGs \\u2014 and a buffered respiratory cluster at y\\u22480'; rewrite caption to describe the concordant_strong vs buffered partition the figure visualizes. The NB00 sphingolipid orientation point can be reduced to one bullet on slide 6 (methods) since slide 16 already carries it.\"\n}\n","numLines":25,"startLine":1,"totalLines":25}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01GM22ZacF4uXpEUzQCKZewP","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01JTfK6pAfwQBJmcuuPSjHMq","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/home/aparkin/BERIL-research-observatory/projects/caulobacter_fur_lipida_loss/talks/draft_1/audit/revisions/F003.slide.json"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3681,"cache_read_input_tokens":15216,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3681},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7dbc6ac5-2e22-4737-9cd1-cf751888377b","uuid":"363f09d4-55f1-4c42-8e40-114c533f7f3c"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01JTfK6pAfwQBJmcuuPSjHMq","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t{\n2\t  \"layout\": \"data_figure\",\n3\t  \"content\": {\n4\t    \"title\": \"NB00: sphingolipid biosynthesis is constitutive across the rescue strain series\",\n5\t    \"figure\": \"figures/00_sphingolipid_locus_heatmap.png\",\n6\t    \"caption\": \"Sphingolipid locus log2(CPM+1) heatmap (WT, \\u0394fur \\u0394sspb, intermediate, rescued); pathway is constitutive \\u2014 neither induced nor suppressed \\u2014 ruling out Fur-driven sphingolipid biosynthesis upregulation.\",\n7\t    \"data_source\": \"REPORT.md \\u00a7Phase A; notebooks/00_orientation.ipynb cell 6\"\n8\t  },\n9\t  \"speaker_notes\": \"Before formal hypothesis testing began, the NB00 orientation notebook established a critical reframing. This heatmap shows the sphingolipid biosynthesis gene locus in log2(CPM+1) across all four strains in the series: wild type (4580), the \\u0394fur \\u0394sspb background (4584), the intermediate strain (4659), and the fully rescued \\u0394lpxc strain (4672). The picture is flat to slightly decreasing \\u2014 not induced.\\n\\nThis eliminated the simplest version of the Fur story: 'Fur normally represses sphingolipid biosynthesis, so \\u0394fur derepresses it, giving the cell extra CPG to substitute for lipid A.' That mechanism would predict the sphingolipid locus going UP in 4584 and UP further in 4672. The data show the opposite \\u2014 the pathway is constitutive. The CPG pool is already standing in wild type; rescue is not a matter of making more sphingolipid in response to lipid A loss.\\n\\nThis observation redirected the analysis. The question became not 'why does \\u0394fur induce sphingolipid biosynthesis?' but 'given that the CPG pool is already present, what Fur-released components enable its trafficking into the outer membrane?' That question frames Layer 1 \\u2014 and the fitness data answer it: the Fur-released TonB-dependent transporters and iron-uptake systems (Path A) carry the envelope-stress fitness signal, plausibly because they are the transport machinery enabling CPG routing to the outer membrane via the shared Lpt apparatus (Uchendu 2026 bioRxiv).\\n\\nCaveat: this orientation figure uses CPM normalization from NB00 and is descriptive rather than statistically DE-tested. The formal characterization of sphingolipid biosynthesis constitutivity with FDR-corrected statistics \\u2014 spt logFC -0.64 FDR 0.002, sphk -0.40 FDR 0.02, zero of six biosynthesis genes significantly UP \\u2014 belongs to NB04 in Layer 3. What the speaker highlights here is the conceptual reframing the figure motivates, not the statistical support that comes later in S3. The delivery note: 'NB00 showed us the sphingolipid pool is already there; the question Layer 1 answers is how Fur derepression routes it.'\\n\\nTransition: with this orientation established \\u2014 Fur derepresses transport, not sphingolipid biosynthesis \\u2014 we turn to the fitness data to ask which part of the Fur regulon actually carries phenotypic weight under envelope stress.\",\n10\t  \"id\": 7,\n11\t  \"substory_id\": \"S1\",\n12\t  \"position\": 7\n13\t}\n14\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7dbc6ac5-2e22-4737-9cd1-cf751888377b","uuid":"af71843e-eef3-4716-9956-ecb12b48456d","timestamp":"2026-06-07T16:32:56.220Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/aparkin/BERIL-research-observatory/projects/caulobacter_fur_lipida_loss/talks/draft_1/audit/revisions/F003.slide.json","content":"{\n  \"layout\": \"data_figure\",\n  \"content\": {\n    \"title\": \"NB00: sphingolipid biosynthesis is constitutive across the rescue strain series\",\n    \"figure\": \"figures/00_sphingolipid_locus_heatmap.png\",\n    \"caption\": \"Sphingolipid locus log2(CPM+1) heatmap (WT, \\u0394fur \\u0394sspb, intermediate, rescued); pathway is constitutive \\u2014 neither induced nor suppressed \\u2014 ruling out Fur-driven sphingolipid biosynthesis upregulation.\",\n    \"data_source\": \"REPORT.md \\u00a7Phase A; notebooks/00_orientation.ipynb cell 6\"\n  },\n  \"speaker_notes\": \"Before formal hypothesis testing began, the NB00 orientation notebook established a critical reframing. This heatmap shows the sphingolipid biosynthesis gene locus in log2(CPM+1) across all four strains in the series: wild type (4580), the \\u0394fur \\u0394sspb background (4584), the intermediate strain (4659), and the fully rescued \\u0394lpxc strain (4672). The picture is flat to slightly decreasing \\u2014 not induced.\\n\\nThis eliminated the simplest version of the Fur story: 'Fur normally represses sphingolipid biosynthesis, so \\u0394fur derepresses it, giving the cell extra CPG to substitute for lipid A.' That mechanism would predict the sphingolipid locus going UP in 4584 and UP further in 4672. The data show the opposite \\u2014 the pathway is constitutive. The CPG pool is already standing in wild type; rescue is not a matter of making more sphingolipid in response to lipid A loss.\\n\\nThis observation redirected the analysis. The question became not 'why does \\u0394fur induce sphingolipid biosynthesis?' but 'given that the CPG pool is already present, what Fur-released components enable its trafficking into the outer membrane?' That question frames Layer 1 \\u2014 and the fitness data answer it: the Fur-released TonB-dependent transporters and iron-uptake systems (Path A) carry the envelope-stress fitness signal, plausibly because they are the transport machinery enabling CPG routing to the outer membrane via the shared Lpt apparatus (Uchendu 2026 bioRxiv).\\n\\nCaveat: this orientation figure uses CPM normalization from NB00 and is descriptive rather than statistically DE-tested. The formal characterization of sphingolipid biosynthesis constitutivity with FDR-corrected statistics \\u2014 spt logFC -0.64 FDR 0.002, sphk -0.40 FDR 0.02, zero of six biosynthesis genes significantly UP \\u2014 belongs to NB04 in Layer 3. What the speaker highlights here is the conceptual reframing the figure motivates, not the statistical support that comes later in S3. The delivery note: 'NB00 showed us the sphingolipid pool is already there; the question Layer 1 answers is how Fur derepression routes it.'\\n\\nTransition: with this orientation established \\u2014 Fur derepresses transport, not sphingolipid biosynthesis \\u2014 we turn to the fitness data to ask which part of the Fur regulon actually carries phenotypic weight under envelope stress.\",\n  \"id\": 7,\n  \"substory_id\": \"S1\",\n  \"position\": 7\n}\n","numLines":14,"startLine":1,"totalLines":14}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_011SeVXAMd7pHwXxuwVFaXzD","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have both the finding and the slide. Let me analyze:\n\n**Finding F003:**\n- Class: `claim_evidence`\n- Severity: P1\n- Slide ID: 7\n- Issue: The slide shows the NB00 sphingolipid locus heatmap (an S3 finding), but slide 7 is the S1 data_figure slot. S1's substory plan calls for the Fur–Leaden concordance scatter (NB01_fur_signature_scatter.png), which visualizes the Spearman ρ=0.315 concordance anchoring Layer 1. \n\nThe S1 defining quantitative finding lacks visual support in the deck. I need to update slide 7 by replacing the current figure with the Fur–Leaden concordance scatter, then revise the title to highlight the ρ=0.315 correlation and 71% sign agreement across the 93 differentially expressed genes, noting the buffered respiratory cluster. The caption should explain the concordant_strong versus buffered partition. I'm also checking the NB01 image caption in the report to verify the Leaden Δfur logFC comparison details. The `claim_evidence` class is actually supported by this prompt, so I should proceed with the fix rather than halting. The `fix_target` field indicates where the fix should be routed, but the finding class determines whether revise_slide.v1 handles it, and since this class has per-class guidance in my system prompt, I'm in the right place. Looking for the NB01 sections in REPORT.md to verify those quotes.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2920,"cache_read_input_tokens":18897,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2920},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7dbc6ac5-2e22-4737-9cd1-cf751888377b","uuid":"8c95688